```
In `Services/FileService.cs`, the `Move` method contains `Directory.CreateDirectory(Path.GetDirectoryName(destination)!)` with a null-forgiving (`!`) operator. `Path.GetDirectoryName` returns null when the path is a filesystem root; if that ever happens, `Directory.CreateDirectory(null!)` crashes with an opaque `ArgumentNullException`. Replace with a safe pattern: capture `var parent = Path.GetDirectoryName(destination);` and if `parent` is null or empty, throw `ArgumentException("Invalid destination path", nameof(request))` (or a similar clear message — moving a file to a filesystem root is nonsensical within the home-directory sandbox). Otherwise call `Directory.CreateDirectory(parent)`. Do not change any other Move behavior. The lazy `Root` accessor added by task-16 must be used in place of the previous `_root` field. Verification: `dotnet test TestProject.Tests/TestProject.Tests.csproj` — all `Move_*` tests still pass; the test-writing phase may add a new test for the null-parent case (a destination resolving to the home root itself).

